player.seasonOutlook: Washington selected Brown in the third round of April's draft. The North Carolina product is a thin (6-foot-1, 189 pounds) perimeter target. His game is the deep ball, as his 16.3 aDOT over the past three seasons is one of the highest in this year's rookie class. Brown is tough and decent route-runner and ball-tracker, but he lacks agility and has had serious drop issues (8.3% since 2018). Brown's route tree was very limited (vertical, hook and shallow routes have been 77% of his game over the past three seasons), but he'll have time to learn the ropes behind Terry McLaurin, Curtis Samuel and Adam Humphries in Washington. Brown's primary value is in dynasty, but keep an eye on his snap counts throughout the 2021 season.

All eyes were on MVP Aaron Rodgers last season, but the Green Bay D/ST quietly posted it's first top-10 fantasy campaign since 2014. Green Bay didn't dominate in any specific category, but was solid across the board, including top-10 showings in sacks and yardage allowed. The 2021 unit will look almost exactly the same, as its top-10 players in 2020 snaps (and 15 of the top 16) remain on the roster and very few veteran additions were made during the offseason. With stars Jaire Alexander, Adrian Amos, Za'Darius Smith and Kenny Clark leading the way, the Packers' D/ST is primed for another season of flirting with top-10 production.

The Bears D/ST has posted fantasy finishes of 15th and, most recently, 17th since its dominant first-place showing back in 2018. The unit has ranked no lower than 12th in points and yardage allowed during each of the past three seasons, but fell just outside the top 10 in both in 2020. Forcing turnovers and sacks have been issues, as the Bears have finished in the bottom half of the league in both categories each of the past two seasons. Two-thirds of the CB room departed during the offseason (Kyle Fuller, Buster Skrine), with Desmond Trufant the only veteran replacement. Khalil Mack, Eddie Jackson, Roquan Smith, Akiem Hicks and 2020 opt-out Eddie Goldman supply this unit with a good core, but the Bears' days as an elite defense appear to be over. Chicago's D/ST is a midrange fantasy option.

Uzomah is far from a household name, so it may surprise you to know that he finished top-20 at tight end in snaps in both 2018 and 2019 and handled five-plus targets in both of his 2020 games prior to suffering a season-ending injury. The TE2-level production isn’t new for Uzomah, as the 2015 fifth-round pick finished 18th at the position in fantasy points in 2018. Uzomah will need to fend off his 2020 replacement Drew Sample for work, but he certainly has a path to a handful of targets each game in Cincinnati’s high-volume scheme. Uzomah’s ceiling isn’t very high, but he’s a viable deep sleeper and should be on your radar in two-TE leagues.

Rob Gronkowski gets the headlines, but it was O.J. Howard who paced the Buccaneers' TE room in passing-game usage and fantasy production prior to a season-ending injury in Week 4. Despite Gronkowski playing more snaps (212 to 125) and running more routes (87 to 58), Howard out-targeted him 19 to 14. Howard posted a 11-146-2 receiving line (fantasy TE17), compared to 9-88-0 (TE36) for Gronkowski. Howard's aDOT was a career-high 11.6, which is notable considering he ranked no lower than third in the category during each of his first three NFL seasons. Howard has yet to complete a 16-game regular season in his career, missing at least two games all four years, but his start to 2020 makes the 26-year-old an interesting sleeper.

Akins emerged as the top fantasy TE in Houston last season, though that's not saying much, as the 2018 third-round pick was held to his second consecutive TE25 fantasy campaign. Akins posted a 36-418-2 receiving line in 2019 before landing on a 37-403-1 line (in 13 games) last season. The 29-year-old is entering a key contract year, but it seems likely that he's already at or near his fantasy ceiling. That's especially the case with Deshaun Watson's future in doubt and with 2019 third-round pick Kahale Warring in the mix for a larger role. Akins doesn't need to be drafted.

After not seeing much work during his first three NFL seasons (74 targets), Patrick was vaulted into a larger workload in 2020. The 2017 UDFA posted a 51-742-6 receiving line on 78 targets and was WR44 in fantasy. He didn't drop a single pass, and his 9.5 YPT was 15th best at the position. Patrick seems to have earned a consistent role in the pros, but he has a lot of competition for targets this season with Courtland Sutton back from injury and youngsters Jerry Jeudy, KJ Hamler and Noah Fant all in the mix. Further complicating the 27-year-old's upside is a run-first Denver offense lacking a proven QB. Patrick is worth your attention only in very deep leagues.

The roller coaster ride that was Goff's five seasons with the Rams came to an end when he was traded to the Lions during the offseason. The 2016 first overall pick reached his peak with top-10 finishes in passing yardage, TDs and YPA during the 2017-18 seasons, but has thus far been able to produce only one top-10 fantasy campaign (seventh in 2018). The primary culprit has been a lack of rushing production, as he's yet to clear 108 yards on the ground in a single season. Goff now joins a rebuilding Lions' team with a few good, young weapons in D'Andre Swift and TJ Hockenson, but without a strong WR room. Goff is a fringe QB2 with little upside.

Wentz is the Colts' new starter after the team acquired him from the Eagles during the offseason. The 2016 second overall pick is coming off a rough 2020 in which he accounted for 21 TDs, 15 INTs, 10 fumbles and career-worst marks in completion rate (57%), YPA (6.0) and off-target rate (league-worst 23%). Wentz had his best NFL season with Colts' coach Frank Reich when both were in Philly in 2017, but that was four seasons ago. Wentz's rough 2020 play, an unproven/underwhelming group of targets and a run-heavy Colts' scheme are likely to limit his fantasy output. The 28-year-old is expected to miss a few weeks to open the season and should only be drafted in superflex leagues.

Bridgewater was traded to Denver after one season in Carolina. In what was his first season as a full-time starter since 2015, the former first-round pick was serviceable, but not spectacular in 2020. He showed well in completion rate (69%, fifth-best) and YPA (7.6), while racking up 20 TDs and 11 INTs. Bridgewater appeared in 15 games, but his conservative nature (7.3 average depth of throw) and the team's run-heavy philosophy near the goal line allowed him only two weekly finishes better than 10th. The 28-year-old adds some juice with his legs, but not quite enough to overcome underwhelming pass production. Even if he beats out Drew Lock for starting duties, Bridgewater would be a fringe QB2.

Darnold is Carolina's new starter after being acquired via trade. Darnold's career is off to a slow start, with various injuries limiting him to no more than 13 games in a single season while with the Jets. The 2018 third-overall pick has racked up a total of 50 TDs, 39 INTs and 20 fumbles while managing only seven top-7 fantasy weeks (one in 2020) in 38 games. He's shown poorly in completion percentage, YPA and INT% (to name a few) all three seasons and hasn't added much with his legs. Darnold has yet to finish a season better than 25th in fantasy points per game. Darnold is only 24 years old, so there's hope for a revival in Carolina, but he's far from a sure thing and thus barely in the QB2 discussion.

Newton's time in New England started very well with a pair of top-six fantasy weeks to open the 2020 season, but he struggled in Week 3, landed on the COVID list and never quite recovered, managing only one weekly finish better than eighth after Week 5. He ended up QB15 for the season. The 32-year-old's supporting cast is better this season and we know he'll put up big numbers on the ground (he finished top-3 at QB in rush attempts, yards and TDs last season), but a lack of passing production (he had eight pass TDs in 15 games) is sure to cap his ceiling. It's also very likely that first-round pick Mac Jones will start, at least, several games. Newton will be a fringe QB1 early on, but he's worth no more than a late flier.

The Chargers selected Palmer in the third round of April's draft. The Tennessee product is a 6-foot-2, 210-pound receiver who lived on hook and vert routes (55% of his tree) and saw a lot of deep targets (16.0 aDOT) during his past three seasons at Tennessee. Palmer had to deal with shaky QB play (31% of targets were uncatchable), but did well to overcome that with reliable hands (four drops on 163 targets). He's not a threat to Keenan Allen or Mike Williams in the short term, but could overtake Jalen Guyton and Tyron Johnson for No. 3 duties very quickly. That would make him a fantasy sleeper considering how good Justin Herbert looked as a rookie. Palmer makes for a fine later flier in deeper leagues.

Bourne signed with New England after spending his first four seasons in San Francisco. The 2017 UDFA has yet to finish a season better than 60th in fantasy points (2020). Fueled by a roster overloaded with injuries, Bourne was forced into a career-high 74 targets last season. He posted a 49-667-2 receiving line and now has nine scores in 58 career games. The 26-year-old joins a run-heavy Patriots' offense that also includes Nelson Agholor, Jakobi Meyers, N'Keal Harry, Jonnu Smith, Hunter Henry and James White. Even if Bourne locks down a consistent role, he's a long shot for anything close to consistent flex value. He's worth your consideration only in very deep formats.

Perine appeared in 10 games and played 188 snaps as a rookie after being drafted in the fourth round of the 2020 draft. Perine struggled to produce in the Jets' weak offensive, putting up 295 yards and two TDs on 75 touches. His efficiency (3.6 YPC, 1.0 YAC, 3.9 YPT) was poor, albeit on a small sample. Perine is 5-foot-11, 216 pounds with underwhelming elusiveness and speed (4.62 40-yard dash), but decent pass-catching chops. He'll battle for snaps with fourth-round rookie Michael Carter and Tevin Coleman in what is one of the league's shakiest RB rooms, so he certainly belongs on the deep sleeper radar. Consider him with a late pick in deep leagues.

McFarland was limited to 33 carries and 11 targets on 87 snaps in his first NFL season. The 2020 fourth-round pick was buried behind the likes of James Conner, Benny Snell Jr. and Jaylen Samuels, maxing out at 14 snaps played in Week 12. Conner is gone, but the 23-year-old is now battling for reserve snaps behind new lead back, rookie Najee Harris. Even if Harris were to miss time, McFarland would be ticketed for committee work alongside Snell and perhaps Samuels. McFarland is not a particularly inspiring hold in dynasty leagues, let alone in season-long formats.

McKinnon signed with the Chiefs and, believe it or not, 2021 will mark the journeyman's eighth season in the league. The 29-year-old spent the past three seasons with the 49ers but missed all of 2018 and 2019 due to injury. He appeared in 16 games last season but was limited to 33% of the snaps. McKinnon struggled to 319 yards on 81 carries (3.9 YPC, 1.5 YAC) and 253 yards on 46 targets (5.5 YPT). McKinnon is unlikely to emerge into a consistent fantasy option, but he needs to be on watch lists because of the uncertain running back situation in Kansas City's high-scoring offense. Unproven Clyde Edwards-Helaire is atop the depth chart, with McKinnon set to compete with Darrel Williams for backup duties.

Reynolds is now with the Titans after spending his first four seasons with the Rams. The 2017 fourth-round pick has primarily worked as a situational player, with the career-high marks he set last season in targets (81), receptions (51) and receiving yards (609) all ranking outside the top 50 at WR. Reynolds has yet to post a top-60 fantasy campaign and his 1.21 YPRR is third worst among 66 WRs with 200-plus targets since he was drafted. The 26-year-old will compete with the likes of Cameron Batson and rookie Dez Fitzpatrick for No. 3 duties behind A.J. Brown and Julio Jones in a Tennessee offense that will lean heavily on that duo and a Derrick Henry-led running game. Consistent usage and production is unlikely, so Reynolds is only worth a look in very deep leagues.

After finishing 27th or worse in fantasy points three consecutive seasons, the Giants' D/ST made the leap to 14th in 2020. The unit had a bit of luck in the fumble department (14 forced, 11 recovered), but was otherwise solid in nearly every fantasy-relevant category. That includes top-12 finishes in points and yardage allowed. Dalvin Tomlinson was an offseason loss of significance, but Leonard Williams and Dexter Lawrence remain in what is one of the league's best DT groups. The Giants' secondary is in very good shape, especially after Adoree' Jackson was signed to join James Bradberry, Jabrill Peppers, Logan Ryan and 2020 second-round pick Xavier McKinney. This is a solid defense and a midrange fantasy D/ST option.

Arizona's D/ST is in the best shape it's been in a long time after last season's 11th-place finish and an offseason that included the additions of J.J. Watt, Malcolm Butler and first-round pick Zaven Collins. Arizona ranked seventh in forced fumbles and, despite missing Chandler Jones for most of its games, fourth in sacks (48) last season. The unit did lose some significant contributors, including Patrick Peterson, De'Vondre Campbell and Haason Reddick, but offset them with the aforementioned acquisitions, and should get more out of 2020 first-round pick Isaiah Simmons this season. Add the likes of Budda Baker, Byron Murphy and Markus Golden to the mix and Arizona's D/ST has the look of a viable streaming option.

Doyle is entering his ninth NFL season - all with the Colts - after posting a 23-251-3 receiving line in 2020. Aside of an injury-plagued 2018, Doyle entered last season having ripped off three consecutive top-15 fantasy campaigns and, coupled with the departure of Eric Ebron, seemed to be positioned for a fourth. Instead, he shared work with Trey Burton and Mo-Alie Cox while handling a weak 2.9 targets per game. Doyle is sure handed (seven drops on 364 career targets) and working in a TE-friendly scheme (in seven seasons, Frank Reich's offenses have a 27% TE target share), but his dip in usage and lack of scoring (has never had more than five TDs in a season) leaves the 31-year-old well off the fantasy radar.

Hurst struggled for playing time during his first two NFL seasons, but that changed when he was traded to Atlanta last year. Hurst played 69% of the snaps and averaged what was easily a career-high 5.6 targets per game. Hurst finished third at TE in pass routes and ranked no lower than 10th in targets, receptions, TDs and fantasy points. There was some hope Hurst might make another leap with Arthur Smith running the offense (Tennessee ranked fifth in TE target share during his two seasons calling plays), but that was destroyed when Atlanta selected Kyle Pitts with the fourth-overall pick of April's draft. With his workload potentially cut in half this season, the 28-year-old Hurst is no longer a viable TE2.

Arnold signed with Carolina after spending the past two seasons in Arizona. Arnold entered the NFL as an undrafted WR back in 2017, but successfully made the transition to tight end over the past few years. After totaling 20 catches in his first two NFL seasons, Arnold played 41% of Arizona's snaps and posted a solid 31-438-4 receiving line in 2020. Arnold's 12.5 aDOT was tops among TEs and his efficiency was terrific, as he caught 72% of his targets (14th) and averaged 10.2 YPT (third). Limited volume (43 targets) allowed him one top-12 fantasy week, but he now has an opportunity to win a job that allowed Ian Thomas 417 pass routes (10th-most among TEs) last season. Arnold is likely still improving and situated well for a potential breakout. The 26-year-old belongs on your sleeper list.

Schultz was the No. 11-scoring TE in fantasy last season, ranking no lower than fifth at the position in snaps (942), routes (500) and receptions (63). After totaling 120 yards on 18 targets during his first two NFL seasons, the 2018 fourth-round pick exploded for a 63-615-4 receiving line on 88 targets. Of course, Schultz would not have been close to those numbers had starter Blake Jarwin not gone down for the season with a torn ACL in Week 1. The two tight ends are expected to battle for the top job in 2021, though a healthy Jarwin would figure to have the leg up. Dallas operates a high-volume, high-scoring offense, so Schultz is worth a late pick in leagues that start multiple tight ends.

Buffalo's offense exploded into a pass-heavy, high-scoring juggernaut in 2020, but Knox was one of the few players who failed to benefit. The 2019 third-round pick was on the field for 60% of the snaps during 15 active weeks (including three playoff games), but was limited to 3.7 targets per game. Knox's usage did increase down the stretch, but he still failed to post a weekly fantasy finish better than 10th (his best-career fantasy week was seventh in Week 3 of 2019). In Knox's defense, a TE-high 33% of balls thrown his way were off target and his 6.8 RAC was second-best at the position. A leap to the TE1 mix seems unlikely, but the 24-year-old is worth monitoring as a deep sleeper.

If "boom/bust" had a name, it would be Marquez Valdes-Scantling. Despite playing 74% of Green Bay's snaps last season (at least 49% in all 18 games), the 2018 fifth-round pick posted some wild splits. He put up 17-plus fantasy points in six games but totaled only 43 points in the other 12 games. That includes five games with zero catches. MVS has some bizarre efficiency stats, as compared to the 62 WRs with 185-plus targets since he was drafted, he ranks last in catch rate (51.1%), third in drop rate (6.3%), second in aDOT (15.5) and second in RAC (6.3). Valdes-Scantling has never finished a season better than 55th in fantasy points and the 26-year-old is a longshot to do so in a similar role in 2021. His best value is as a DFS tournament punt.

Taylor signed with the Texans during the offseason. The 32-year-old dual-threat QB has attempted only 121 passes over the past three seasons after losing starting gigs with the Browns and Chargers. Taylor has never appeared in a full 16-game regular season and his best fantasy finish was ninth in 2016. His game is built on minimizing turnovers (18 INTs on 1,357 attempts since 2015) and rushing (top-3 at QB in rushing yards each season from 2015-17), though it doesn't lead to much passing production, as he's never cleared 3,035 yards or 20 TDs through the air. Taylor will leap into the QB2 discussion only if he replaces Deshaun Watson (legal issues) in Houston.

The Jets D/ST has managed one top-20 fantasy showing over the past five seasons, but new defensive-minded coach Robert Saleh is a good bet to inject some life into the unit in 2021. New York finished 20th or worse in sacks, yardage allowed, points allowed and forced turnovers in last season, whereas Saleh's 49ers' unit dominated in those categories when last healthy in 2019. The Jets' defense is a work in progress with notable voids (especially at cornerback), but there are plenty of positives, including incumbent stars Quinnen Williams and Marcus Maye, the healthy return of C.J. Mosley and Blake Cashman, and impact newcomers Carl Lawson, Sheldon Rankins, Jarrad Davis and Lamarcus Joyner. Consider the Jets' D/ST a mid-pack fantasy unit.

The Chiefs' D/ST was one of fantasy's top units a half decade ago, but has now posted four consecutive finishes outside the top 10, including a 15th-place finish in 2020. Kansas City has had a decent floor, however, ranking 17th or better each of the past eight seasons. The reason? The Chiefs have consistently shined in two departments, ranking no lower than ninth in INTs each of the past six seasons and no lower than 10th in D/ST TDs each of the past eight seasons. The unit has some clear weak spots, but also some star power in the form of Chris Jones, Frank Clark and Tyrann Mathieu. Mecole Hardman adds value, as he has a return TD each of the past two seasons. Consider this a midrange fantasy D/ST.
